### 🚫 Anti-Patterns to Avoid

#### 1. Direct Scene References
```csharp
// ❌ DON'T hardcode scene names everywhere
SceneManager.LoadScene("GameScene");

// ✅ DO use SceneLoader utility
SceneLoader.LoadGameScene(GameMode.InfiniteStacker);
```

#### 2. Singleton Pattern (use DependencyRegistry instead)
```csharp
// ❌ DON'T create traditional singletons
public static GameManager Instance { get; private set; }

// ✅ DO use DependencyRegistry
var gameManager = DependencyRegistry.Find<GameManager>();
```

#### 3. Finding Objects in Update/FixedUpdate
```csharp
// ❌ NEVER do this
private void Update()
{
    var manager = DependencyRegistry.Find<GameManager>(); // BAD!
}

// ✅ DO cache references in Start
private GameManager gameManager;
private void Start()
{
    gameManager = DependencyRegistry.Find<GameManager>();
}
```

#### 4. Public Fields for Configuration
```csharp
// ❌ Don't use public fields
public float speed;

// ✅ Use [SerializeField] private fields
[SerializeField] private float speed = 5f;
```

---

### 📚 ScriptableObject Pattern

#### Level Data
```csharp
// ✅ Use ScriptableObjects for data
[CreateAssetMenu(fileName = "NewLevel", menuName = "TamalStacker/Level Data")]
public class LevelData : ScriptableObject
{
    public int levelNumber;
    public int requiredStackHeight;
    // ... more properties
}
```

---

### ⚡ Performance Guidelines

#### 1. Cache Component References
```csharp
// ✅ Cache in Start
private Transform cachedTransform;
private void Start()
{
    cachedTransform = transform;
}

// ❌ Don't access repeatedly
private void Update()
{
    transform.position = ...; // Slower
}
```

#### 2. Use Object Pooling for Frequent Instantiation
```csharp
// For spawned blocks, consider using an object pool
```

#### 3. Minimize Allocations in Update
```csharp
// ❌ Avoid allocations in Update
private void Update()
{
    string text = "Score: " + score; // Creates garbage
}

// ✅ Cache or use StringBuilder
private StringBuilder scoreBuilder = new StringBuilder();
```

---

### 🎯 Project-Specific Rules

#### GameManager Configuration
- Always check "Wait For Game Mode Selection" in Inspector
- Always check "Auto Start After Mode Set" in Inspector

#### Scene Structure
- MainMenu scene: Independent, contains MainMenuManager
- GameScene: Contains game logic, UIManager
- GameManager persists across scenes

#### Settings System
- SettingsManager registers in Awake
- Settings are applied in ApplySettings()
- Always call SaveSettings() after changes

---

### ✅ Code Review Checklist

Before committing code, verify:

- [ ] Used DependencyRegistry.Register in Awake
- [ ] Used DependencyRegistry.Find in Start
- [ ] Used DependencyRegistry.Unregister in OnDestroy
- [ ] No FindObjectOfType or similar methods
- [ ] Event subscriptions have matching unsubscriptions
- [ ] Null checks before using references
- [ ] Public API has XML documentation
- [ ] SerializeField used instead of public fields
- [ ] No hardcoded strings for scenes/paths
- [ ] PlayerPrefs keys are descriptive and consistent

---

### 🔄 When Adding New Manager Components

Follow this template:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;

/// <summary>
/// Brief description of what this manager does
/// </summary>
public class NewManager : MonoBehaviour
{
    [Header("Settings")]
    [SerializeField] private float exampleSetting = 1.0f;
    
    // References (found via DependencyRegistry)
    private GameManager gameManager;
    
    // State
    private bool isInitialized = false;
    
    private void Awake()
    {
        // 1. Register with DependencyRegistry
        DependencyRegistry.Register<NewManager>(this);
        
        // 2. Optional: Persist across scenes if needed
        // DontDestroyOnLoad(gameObject);
    }
    
    private void Start()
    {
        // 1. Find dependencies
        gameManager = DependencyRegistry.Find<GameManager>();
        
        // 2. Subscribe to events
        if (gameManager != null)
        {
            gameManager.OnGameStart += OnGameStart;
        }
        
        // 3. Initialize
        Initialize();
    }
    
    private void Initialize()
    {
        // Initialization logic
        isInitialized = true;
    }
    
    private void OnGameStart()
    {
        // Event handler
    }
    
    private void OnDestroy()
    {
        // 1. Unregister
        DependencyRegistry.Unregister<NewManager>(this);
        
        // 2. Unsubscribe from events
        if (gameManager != null)
        {
            gameManager.OnGameStart -= OnGameStart;
        }
    }
}
```

---

## Summary

**Core Principles:**
1. ✅ Always use DependencyRegistry (Register in Awake, Find in Start, Unregister in OnDestroy)
2. ❌ Never use FindObjectOfType or similar Unity search methods
3. ✅ Always unsubscribe from events in OnDestroy
4. ✅ Use SceneLoader for scene transitions
5. ✅ Follow consistent lifecycle patterns
6. ✅ Document public APIs with XML comments
7. ✅ Cache references, don't search repeatedly
8. ✅ Use null checks before accessing references

**When in doubt, look at existing managers (GameManager, UIManager, LevelManager) as examples!**

